# Go Library Patterns

- Prefer straightforward exported APIs with minimal indirection.
- Reuse the package pattern already common here: `type Config struct { ... }`, `func New(...)`, then receiver methods on the client/value.
- Return errors instead of panicking or exiting when initialization or I/O can fail.
- When adding context to an error, use `fmt.Errorf("...: %w", err)`.
- Accept `context.Context` for operations tied to I/O, request scope, or transactions.
- Keep implementations compact and readable; avoid premature interfaces and unnecessary generics.
- Use zero or near-zero dependencies beyond what the package already needs.
- Add comments sparingly, mainly for behavior, constraints, or non-obvious tradeoffs.
- Stay consistent with existing package naming, receiver naming, and field visibility choices.
